ds','','inherit','open','open','','1239-revision-3','','','2012-01-01 23:39:26','2012-01-01 15:39:26','',1239,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1239-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(3825,1,'2012-01-23 10:14:54','2012-01-23 02:14:54','','Definitions of Cross Elasticity of Demand','','inherit','open','open','','1104-revision','','','2012-01-23 10:14:54','2012-01-23 02:14:54','',1104,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1104-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(3827,1,'2012-01-23 10:14:55','2012-01-23 02:14:55','','Definitions of Income Elasticity of Demand','','inherit','open','open','','1100-revision','','','2012-01-23 10:14:55','2012-01-23 02:14:55','',1100,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1100-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(3829,1,'2012-01-23 10:14:55','2012-01-23 02:14:55','','Coefficients of Price Elasticity of Demand','','inherit','open','open','','1096-revision-3','','','2012-01-23 10:14:55','2012-01-23 02:14:55','',1096,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1096-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(1778,1,'2011-10-08 10:36:36','2011-10-08 02:36:36','httpvh://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A6d_1FCzTyI\n\nHere’s a tip. To do explanations without missing out on major points, always use frameworks. For elasticities, always identify 3 main things when explaining them in a question:\n<ol>\n<li>The definition of the elasticity. eg. For PED, it is “the responsiveness of quantity demanded of a good to a change in its price, <em>ceteris paribus</em></li>\n<li>The sign of the coefficient of the elasticity eg. For PED, the sign of the coefficient is always negative (because quantity demanded increases when price decreases)</li>\n<li>The value of the coefficient of the elasticity e.g. A price inelastic good has a low value for the coefficient</li>\n</ol>\nThis is the framework that we use for explaining elasticities.\n\nYou will encounter the term “ceteris paribus” very often. This is Latin for \"with other things the same.\" You can interpret this to mean that the whole world stays constant except for the two variables in question. The concept of “ceteris paribus” is in itself potentially misleading – simply because the world never stays still. However, for the purposes of economic modelling and simplification in analysis, the ceteris paribus clause is extremely useful. \n\nFor the science students, think of it as serving a similar purpose as the “assume that there is no friction” clause in Physics examinations, or the fact that in Chemistry questions you are assumed to have superhuman precision in mixing reagents. Imagine doing a chemical reaction question when you have to take into account the shakiness of the scientist’s hands, the cleanliness of the flask, minute temperature differences in the surrounding areas. These variables do change in real life. However, we assume them away simply because they don’t affect the results much. Likewise in Economics, we use the “ceteris paribus” clause to shut out variables that we assume insignificant to the question at hand.','Framework for Analysing Elasticity','','inherit','open','open','','1092-autosave','','','2011-10-08 10:36:36','2011-10-08 02:36:36','',1092,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1092-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(3195,1,'2011-12-30 00:13:44','2011-12-29 16:13:44','','Definition of Price Elasticity of Demand','','inherit','open','open','','1094-revision','','','2011-12-30 00:13:44','2011-12-29 16:13:44','',1094,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1094-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(3249,25,'2012-01-23 20:20:23','2012-01-23 12:20:23','','[02] Limiting Reagents and Excess Reactants','','publish','open','open','','02-limiting-reagents-and-excess-reactants','','','2012-02-04 01:07:17','2012-02-03 17:07:17','',0,'http://openlectures.sg/?p=3249',0,'post','',0),(3251,25,'2012-01-23 20:20:56','2012-01-23 12:20:56','','[03] Types of Reactions','','publish','open','open','','03-types-of-reactions','','','2012-02-04 01:07:17','2012-02-03 17:07:17','',0,'http://openlectures.sg/?p=3251'